00:44:49,453 --> 00:44:50,955
it's the best thing I've ever thrown up.

547
00:45:09,773 --> 00:45:11,081
Liesel!

548
00:45:11,642 --> 00:45:13,747
I have a job for you.

549
00:45:22,653 --> 00:45:24,997
And don't forget to count the money.

550
00:45:26,957 --> 00:45:28,129
Come back with the right amount

551
00:45:28,225 --> 00:45:30,501
or don't bother coming back at all.

552
00:45:56,153 --> 00:45:58,326
<i>The Burgermeister's house.</i>

553
00:45:59,656 --> 00:46:01,567
Are you sure?

554
00:46:02,326 --> 00:46:05,432
Do you see any other houses
looking like this?

555
00:46:06,930 --> 00:46:10,070
He had dinner with the Fuhrer once.

556
00:46:30,087 --> 00:46:32,567
(GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING)

557
00:46:49,473 --> 00:46:50,884
(KNOCKING)

558
00:47:00,684 --> 00:47:01,958
Laundry.

559
00:47:02,820 --> 00:47:03,798
Come in.

560
00:47:08,125 --> 00:47:09,160
Go on.

561
00:47:27,411 --> 00:47:28,685
(DOOR CLOSING)

562
00:47:44,895 --> 00:47:46,238
Wait.

563
00:48:07,718 --> 00:48:08,822
<i>LIESEL: Dan/re beautiful.</i>

564
00:48:17,294 --> 00:48:18,466
So, you like books?

565
00:48:33,644 --> 00:48:34,679
Come.

566
00:49:45,615 --> 00:49:47,788
<i>"The Dream Carrier. "</i>

567
00:50:10,640 --> 00:50:11,880
Rudy.

568
00:50:14,544 --> 00:50:15,545
I have to go.

569
00:50:19,483 --> 00:50:22,362
You can come back whenever you want.

570
00:50:22,552 --> 00:50:24,327
It will be here.

571
00:50:27,190 --> 00:50:28,794
Yes, Frau Hermann.

572
00:50:32,095 --> 00:50:34,166
Call me "Ilsa."

573
00:50:34,364 --> 00:50:36,207
What shall I call you?

574
00:50:37,801 --> 00:50:38,779
Liesel.

575
00:50:43,040 --> 00:50:45,179
You are a brave girl, Liesel.

576
00:50:58,855 --> 00:51:00,198
RUDY: Come back, Saumensch!

577
00:51:00,590 --> 00:51:01,898
Catch me!

578
00:51:03,727 --> 00:51:05,434
Hey, fool! Did you hear?

579
00:51:05,529 --> 00:51:08,271
England declared war on us!
We're at war with England!

580
00:51:08,498 --> 00:51:09,738
(CHEERING)

581
00:51:12,669 --> 00:51:14,046
We're at war!

582
00:51:15,272 --> 00:51:17,047
England declared war!

583
00:51:17,140 --> 00:51:23,421
<i>NARRATOR: It's always been
the same, the excitement and rush to war.</i>

584
00:51:23,613 --> 00:51:26,093
<i>I've met so many young men
over the years...</i>

585
00:51:26,283 --> 00:51:29,264
<i>who have thought
they were running at their enemy.</i>

586
00:51:29,453 --> 00:51:33,094
<i>When the truth was,
they were running to me.</i>

587
00:51:35,492 --> 00:51:36,630
(CROWD CHEERING)

588
00:51:47,003 --> 00:51:48,073
<i>Yes !</i>

589
00:51:50,107 --> 00:51:51,108
Excellent.

590
00:51:52,676 --> 00:51:54,451
(THANKING IN GERMAN)

591
00:52:01,985 --> 00:52:04,329
You should look
where you're going next time.

592
00:52:06,256 --> 00:52:07,701
Drop dead, Franz.

593
00:52:09,292 --> 00:52:12,569
What's up, Jesse Owens?
I thought you liked being black.

594
00:52:18,535 --> 00:52:19,513
(KNOCKING)

595
00:52:35,952 --> 00:52:37,329
Who is Johann?

596
00:52:40,524 --> 00:52:43,368
He used to love to read.

597
00:52:44,861 --> 00:52:47,239
And he was brave. Just like you.

598
00:52:50,033 --> 00:52:52,639
This is all him. Everything he knew.

599
00:52:53,670 --> 00:52:54,944
All here.

600
00:52:55,805 --> 00:52:56,909
All in its place.

601
00:53:09,519 --> 00:53:11,226
They never found his body.

602
00:53:14,157 --> 00:53:17,661
If they could have shown me his
body, I would have believed them.

603
00:53:18,228 --> 00:53:20,401
But how can a mother give up?

604
00:53:22,232 --> 00:53:25,179
A mother never gives up on her child.

605
00:53:29,906 --> 00:53:31,647
I have to go.

606
00:53:53,530 --> 00:53:55,703
Do you think my mother really loved me?

607
00:53:57,267 --> 00:53:58,940
Of course.

608
00:54:01,304 --> 00:54:03,614
Every mother loves her child.

609
00:54:05,308 --> 00:54:07,015
Even Hitler's.

610
00:54:11,881 --> 00:54:14,794
Do you think she writes to him?

611
00:54:25,028 --> 00:54:26,063
" D <i>ea</i> r <i>Fuhrer...</i>

612
00:54:28,231 --> 00:54:30,973
"just wait until your father gets home.

613
00:54:31,167 --> 00:54:32,908
"Love, Mama."

614
00:54:33,603 --> 00:54:36,049
"Dear Fuhrer, clean up your mess."

615
00:54:36,273 --> 00:54:38,446
"Dear Fuhrer, who cut your hair?"

616
00:54:38,708 --> 00:54:40,483
"You're not going out in that, are you?"

617
00:54:41,278 --> 00:54:42,757
"What's that growing on your lip?"

618
00:54:42,979 --> 00:54:44,720
"Don't raise your voice at me."

619
00:54:45,015 --> 00:54:46,323
"Stop spitting when you yell."

620
00:54:46,483 --> 00:54:47,791
(LAUGHING)

621
00:54:59,996 --> 00:55:01,100
Hans...

622
00:55:02,132 --> 00:55:03,634
he's getting bedsores.

623
00:55:04,501 --> 00:55:06,538
HANS: Then he needs to
get up and move about.

624
00:55:07,537 --> 00:55:09,608
He can't just walk around.

625
00:55:09,806 --> 00:55:10,784
LIESEL: Why not?

626
00:55:10,974 --> 00:55:12,681
Because people will see in.

627
00:55:12,909 --> 00:55:14,217
(SHUSHING)

628
00:55:15,545 --> 00:55:18,788
He can't lay still forever.
He needs to be moved.

629
00:55:20,317 --> 00:55:21,295
Why?

630
00:55:22,285 --> 00:55:24,629
The mouth on it! Because I say so.

631
00:55:24,821 --> 00:55:25,799
Rosa.

632
00:55:25,989 --> 00:55:27,491
And what do you propose?

633
00:55:27,957 --> 00:55:30,301
"Propose"? Listen to this one.

634
00:55:30,794 --> 00:55:33,172
I propose that we put him downstairs.

635
00:55:42,105 --> 00:55:44,210
It's not good, we know that.

636
00:55:47,210 --> 00:55:48,188
I'm sorry.

637
00:55:48,378 --> 00:55:51,985
Please don't apologize.
I've put you all in such danger.

638
00:55:52,182 --> 00:55:53,490
It's more than I deserve.

639
00:55:54,417 --> 00:55:57,023
Liesel's lessons. It is a dictionary.

640
00:55:57,721 --> 00:55:59,962
I tried to make it as comfortable as I could.

641
00:56:05,395 --> 00:56:06,806
I'm sorry, there's no bed.

642
00:56:08,398 --> 00:56:10,400
If anyone saw, you know?

643
00:56:11,101 --> 00:56:13,741
You feel free
to do your lessons whenever you want.

644
00:56:13,937 --> 00:56:16,110
Make sure you knock first.

645
00:56:18,908 --> 00:56:20,854
I'm just downstairs.
I'm not going anywhere.

646
00:56:22,045 --> 00:56:23,251
Promise.

647
00:56:49,205 --> 00:56:50,616
Don't give me that look.

648
00:57:04,354 --> 00:57:05,924
"Jellyfish."

649
00:57:06,589 --> 00:57:08,091
"Jellyfish."

650
00:57:08,224 --> 00:57:09,202
Jellyfish.

651
00:57:20,203 --> 00:57:22,979
Tell me, where do you get these words?

652
00:57:26,443 --> 00:57:27,717
It's a secret.

653
00:57:29,512 --> 00:57:31,321
And who would I tell?

654
00:57:35,452 --> 00:57:37,762
Th e Burgermeister's wife.

655
00:57:38,822 --> 00:57:40,995
She lets me read her books.

656
00:57:41,558 --> 00:57:43,367
I memorize them.

657
00:57:45,228 --> 00:57:47,902
"Memory is the scribe of the soul."

658
00:57:49,365 --> 00:57:50,571
Do you know who said that?

659
00:57:53,036 --> 00:57:55,539
A man called Aristotle.

660
00:57:57,173 --> 00:57:58,811
Can you do me a favor?

661
00:57:59,375 --> 00:58:01,753
Can you describe the day for me?

662
00:58:04,247 --> 00:58:06,386
What's it like outside?

663
00:58:07,050 --> 00:58:08,120
It's cloudy.

664
00:58:08,284 --> 00:58:09,388
No, no, no.

665
00:58:09,853 --> 00:58:11,696
Make the words yours.

666
00:58:14,090 --> 00:58:16,127
If your eyes could speak...

667
00:58:16,826 --> 00:58:18,305
what would they say?

668
00:58:22,098 --> 00:58:25,136
It's a pale day.

669
00:58:25,502 --> 00:58:27,812
"Pale." Good. Go on.

670
00:58:31,508 --> 00:58:34,682
Everything's stuck behind a cloud.

671
00:58:35,712 --> 00:58:38,022
And the sun...

672
00:58:38,615 --> 00:58:40,288
doesn't look like the sun.

673
00:58:40,984 --> 00:58:42,554
What does it look like?

674
00:58:45,655 --> 00:58:49,068
Like a silver oyster?

675
00:58:54,697 --> 00:58:56,142
(CHUCKLES)

676
00:58:57,734 --> 00:59:00,044
Thank you. I saw that.

677
00:59:47,650 --> 00:59:49,425
(WHISPERING) We're hiding a Jew.

678
00:59:49,686 --> 00:59:51,757
(GASPS) Johann?

679
00:59:53,356 --> 00:59:54,528
<i>No.</i>

680
00:59:56,326 --> 00:59:57,600
It's Liesel.

681
00:59:59,128 --> 01:00:00,266
(DOOR OPENING)

682
01:00:05,501 --> 01:00:07,538
What's the meaning of this?

683
01:00:24,554 --> 01:00:26,932
And he didn't say why?

684
01:00:29,926 --> 01:00:31,701
I don't understand it.

685
01:00:31,894 --> 01:00:34,966
I've always ironed
his shirts in exactly the same way.

686
01:00:35,164 --> 01:00:37,166
Maybe they can't afford it any longer.

687
01:00:37,367 --> 01:00:38,869
They can't afford it?

688
01:00:39,836 --> 01:00:41,315
We can't afford it.

689
01:00:45,375 --> 01:00:47,150
It's another customer gone.

690
01:00:47,343 --> 01:00:48,788
And four mouths to feed.

691
01:00:48,878 --> 01:00:50,050
(SHUSHING)

692
01:00:55,251 --> 01:00:56,389
Well.

693
01:00:57,220 --> 01:01:00,895
It's two meals a day from now on, not three.

694
01:01:01,758 --> 01:01:03,135
That's all there is to it.

695
01:01:20,743 --> 01:01:22,552
(INDISTINCT)

696
01:01:31,754 --> 01:01:33,097
I've made you a suit.

697
01:01:35,491 --> 01:01:39,598
I want you to wear it on your 14th birthday.

698
01:01:40,797 --> 01:01:43,209
You'll be back then, Papa.

699
01:01:43,399 --> 01:01:44,969
Won't you?

700
01:02:24,373 --> 01:02:26,580
(ACCORDION PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)

701
01:02:54,604 --> 01:02:55,708
ROSA: Hans!

702
01:02:56,539 --> 01:02:57,517
Rosa...

703
01:02:57,740 --> 01:02:59,720
I'm asking you, I'm begging you...

704
01:02:59,909 --> 01:03:04,289
would you please
keep your mouth shut for five minutes?

705
01:03:10,453 --> 01:03:12,057
I brought you something.

706
01:03:12,255 --> 01:03:14,132
- Is this today's?
- Yes.

707
01:03:14,323 --> 01:03:16,462
A gift from Franz German.

708
01:03:16,659 --> 01:03:19,435
That boy doesn't know how generous he is.

709
01:03:20,596 --> 01:03:22,872
"Hitler poised to take Moscow."

710
01:03:27,270 --> 01:03:29,341
The world has turned mad.

711
01:03:30,973 --> 01:03:32,247
But...

712
01:03:32,809 --> 01:03:34,311
aren't we winning the war?

713
01:03:39,849 --> 01:03:40,850
Max?

714
01:03:48,524 --> 01:03:50,470
Where's my weather report?

715
01:04:05,141 --> 01:04:06,677
You're full of wonders.

716
01:04:08,711 --> 01:04:09,917
I've got an idea.

717
01:04:36,138 --> 01:04:38,414
(MAX AND LIESEL LAUGHING)

718
01:04:53,322 --> 01:04:55,529
What on earth are you doing?

719
01:04:56,092 --> 01:04:57,332
(SHUSHES)

720
01:05:04,033 --> 01:05:05,444
(SHUSHES) Go, go, go!

721
01:05:19,448 --> 01:05:20,426
Max.

722
01:05:24,687 --> 01:05:25,825
I have no more snow!

723
01:05:26,255 --> 01:05:27,700
LIESEL: Get him, Max!

724
01:05:27,890 --> 01:05:30,871
ROSA: What in God's name
are you Saukerle doing down here?

725
01:05:31,027 --> 01:05:32,005
Rosa!

726
01:05:36,232 --> 01:05:39,338
There's a madwoman
on the battlefield! No, <i>No!</i>

727
01:05:40,303 --> 01:05:41,839
I'm unarmed!

728
01:05:44,507 --> 01:05:46,384
<i>(PLAYING SILENT NIGHT)</i>

729
01:06:00,957 --> 01:06:04,404
This is the stupidest thing
that I have ever done.

730
01:06:04,593 --> 01:06:06,630
And look how happy you are.

731
01:06:13,736 --> 01:06:15,215
What do we do when it melts?

732
01:06:15,404 --> 01:06:16,815
<i>You mop it up, Saumensch.</i>

733
01:06:17,006 --> 01:06:19,486
It won't melt. it's freezing down here.

734
01:06:20,509 --> 01:06:22,955
I don't know how you do it every night.

735
01:06:23,145 --> 01:06:24,749
Please, don't think about me.

736
01:06:24,947 --> 01:06:26,893
Nonsense. We all think about you.

737
01:06:29,986 --> 01:06:32,330
This is the best Christmas.

738
01:06:34,423 --> 01:06:36,266
This is my first Christmas.

739
01:06:37,126 --> 01:06:40,369
Now you know
what you've been missing out on.

740
01:06:41,163 --> 01:06:42,642
We should call it a night.

741
01:06:42,832 --> 01:06:44,834
No, Papa. Please.

742
01:06:45,034 --> 01:06:46,104
ROSA: Listen to your father.

743
01:06:46,802 --> 01:06:48,247
You can stay a little longer.

744
01:06:48,437 --> 01:06:50,610
Oh, you're too soft on that girl.

745
01:06:58,881 --> 01:07:00,588
I've made you a Christmas gift.

746
01:07:03,652 --> 01:07:05,131
It's all I had.

747
01:07:21,003 --> 01:07:22,004
But...

748
01:07:22,171 --> 01:07:23,149
Open it.

749
01:07:26,709 --> 01:07:27,710
"For Liesel...

750
01:07:28,377 --> 01:07:29,981
"from Max."

751
01:07:33,716 --> 01:07:35,423
What does it say?

752
01:07:36,719 --> 01:07:37,857
(SPEAKING HEBREW)

753
01:07:40,056 --> 01:07:41,467
"Write."

754
01:07:44,760 --> 01:07:46,398
In my religion...

755
01:07:46,595 --> 01:07:49,633
we're taught that every living thing...

756
01:07:50,199 --> 01:07:52,475
every leaf, every bird...

757
01:07:52,668 --> 01:07:56,673
is only alive
because it contains the secret word for life.

758
01:07:59,075 --> 01:08:03,387
That's the only difference between
us and a lump of clay. A word.

759
01:08:06,215 --> 01:08:08,422
Words are life, Liesel.

760
01:08:10,286 --> 01:08:12,027
All those blank pages...

761
01:08:12,688 --> 01:08:13,928
they're for you to fill.

762
01:08:23,933 --> 01:08:25,241
(SHUDDERING)

763
01:08:27,603 --> 01:08:29,480
(FOOTSTEPS DESCENDING)

764
01:08:44,820 --> 01:08:46,424
My God.

765
01:08:50,893 --> 01:08:52,395
Is he going to die?

766
01:08:52,595 --> 01:08:53,903
Shut up!

767
01:08:54,096 --> 01:08:56,940
I won't have that talk
in this house. Do you understand?

768
01:08:57,433 --> 01:09:00,778
I haven't starved us all
for the better part of two years...

769
01:09:00,970 --> 01:09:03,644
just so that he could die.

770
01:09:06,108 --> 01:09:07,246
It's my fault.

771
01:09:07,910 --> 01:09:09,583
Why is it your fault?

772
01:09:10,079 --> 01:09:12,559
It was my idea to build that snowman.

773
01:09:13,682 --> 01:09:15,423
Why did we build it?

774
01:09:16,919 --> 01:09:18,990
Because we had to.

775
01:09:23,792 --> 01:09:26,932
You said you weren't going anywhere, Max.

776
01:09:27,463 --> 01:09:29,306
You promised.

777
01:09:50,886 --> 01:09:53,423
<i>"The Invisible Man...</i>

778
01:09:53,622 --> 01:09:55,829
"by H.G. Wells."

779
01:10:01,530 --> 01:10:04,306
"The stranger came early in February...

780
01:10:05,034 --> 01:10:06,342
<i>"one wintry day...</i>

781
01:10:06,869 --> 01:10:10,407
<i>"through a biting wind and a driving snow.</i>

782
01:10:11,006 --> 01:10:12,781
<i>"The last snowfall..."</i>

783
01:10:14,043 --> 01:10:16,887
<i>"And none other will know of them...</i>

784
01:10:17,746 --> 01:10:19,225
<i>"until he dies."</i>

785
01:10:21,083 --> 01:10:22,391
<i>"The End."</i>

786
01:10:23,986 --> 01:10:25,522
Max?

787
01:10:34,263 --> 01:10:36,072
"Chapter One."

788
01:11:11,233 --> 01:11:12,337
(GRUNTS)

789
01:11:35,324 --> 01:11:37,497
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

790
01:11:40,329 --> 01:11:41,307
Ilsa?

791
01:11:59,915 --> 01:12:01,360
(DOOR CLOSING)

792
01:12:04,853 --> 01:12:08,266
<i>LIESEL: "The eyes in the faces
he passed an the street...</i>

793
01:12:08,457 --> 01:12:12,132
<i>"seemed to look inside him
and finger his guilt.</i>

794
01:12:12,695 --> 01:12:14,732
<i>"But things were out of his control.</i>

795
01:12:15,764 --> 01:12:17,505
<i>"He had cut himself loose...</i>

796
01:12:17,866 --> 01:12:23,077
"and was drifting
faster and faster towards his fate.

797
01:12:25,541 --> 01:12:27,919
<i>"...was the dustiness of the floor...</i>

798
01:12:28,110 --> 01:12:33,116
<i>"the feeling that the clothes
were more next to he! than on her...</i>

799
01:12:33,782 --> 01:12:38,788
"and the sudden realization
that this would all be for nothing."

800
01:12:42,524 --> 01:12:44,504
- Did you lose something?
- LIESEL: (QUIETLY) Rudy!

801
01:12:45,561 --> 01:12:46,767
What are you doing?

802
01:12:47,029 --> 01:12:48,975
Spying on you, obviously.

803
01:12:49,298 --> 01:12:50,641
Give me that!

804
01:12:51,800 --> 01:12:55,805
So, let me guess.
You forgot where the front door was.

805
01:12:56,839 --> 01:13:00,013
I've got to hand it
to you, Saumensch, you've got guts...

806
01:13:00,409 --> 01:13:02,184
stealing from the Burgermeister.

807
01:13:02,378 --> 01:13:03,880
Keep it down.

808
01:13:04,079 --> 01:13:06,491
I'm not stealing. I'm borrowing.

809
01:13:07,015 --> 01:13:08,153
Whatever you are "borrowing"...

810
01:13:08,350 --> 01:13:09,829
I just wish you let me in on it.

811
01:13:10,018 --> 01:13:11,292
It's not what you think.

812
01:13:11,453 --> 01:13:12,693
Then...

813
01:13:12,921 --> 01:13:14,229
what is it?

814
01:13:15,858 --> 01:13:17,565
I'm borrowing books. That's all.

815
01:13:17,926 --> 01:13:20,167
Books? Are you nuts?

816
01:13:20,362 --> 01:13:22,501
We are starving out here
and you're stealing books?

817
01:13:22,698 --> 01:13:23,870
Stop using that word.

818
01:13:24,400 --> 01:13:27,711
How about food? Did you ever even think
of looking in the kitchen?

819
01:13:27,870 --> 01:13:28,848
<i>No.</i>

820
01:13:29,171 --> 01:13:31,242
We could have
planned this better if you told me.

821
01:13:32,207 --> 01:13:34,380
I'm sorry. I couldn't.

822
01:13:34,576 --> 01:13:38,285
You know, for a best friend,
you keep a lot to yourself.

823
01:13:41,850 --> 01:13:43,420
What's that supposed to mean?

824
01:13:44,353 --> 01:13:45,661
Who's Max?

825
01:13:47,923 --> 01:13:48,993
Who is he?

826
01:13:49,925 --> 01:13:50,995
Liesel!

827
01:13:55,798 --> 01:13:57,709
Tell me what's going on!

828
01:13:58,300 --> 01:14:01,281
<i>Te“ ma, Saumensch, who is he?</i>

829
01:14:02,938 --> 01:14:05,043
Is he your boyfriend?

830
01:14:05,374 --> 01:14:06,717
What?

831
01:14:07,709 --> 01:14:08,915
Is that what you think?

832
01:14:09,311 --> 01:14:10,654
Then what?

833
01:14:11,079 --> 01:14:12,422
Tell me, who is he?

834
01:14:12,748 --> 01:14:14,250
I can't.

835
01:14:14,450 --> 01:14:15,690
Why not?

836
01:14:18,487 --> 01:14:19,625
It's a secret.

837
01:14:20,456 --> 01:14:21,799
You don't trust me?

838
01:14:22,391 --> 01:14:24,803
It's not like that, Rudy. I can't.

839
01:14:25,961 --> 01:14:27,440
If I...

840
01:14:28,130 --> 01:14:31,873
lf l told you, I'd have to go away.

841
01:14:32,901 --> 01:14:35,438
Papa would have to go away.

842
01:14:36,905 --> 01:14:39,317
God knows what would happen to him.

843
01:14:40,309 --> 01:14:41,720
<i>"Him"?</i>

844
01:14:43,312 --> 01:14:45,349
You're hiding someone?

845
01:14:46,982 --> 01:14:49,724
You're hiding someone, aren't you?

846
01:14:50,152 --> 01:14:51,290
Liesel!

847
01:14:54,590 --> 01:14:56,695
One spit, "Yes." Two spits, "No."

848
01:15:04,066 --> 01:15:05,044
I knew it.

849
01:15:06,368 --> 01:15:08,405
No one can know, Rudy.

850
01:15:08,937 --> 01:15:10,075
I mean it.

851
01:15:10,272 --> 01:15:11,910
You can trust me.

852
01:15:12,975 --> 01:15:14,477
Don't worry.

853
01:15:15,043 --> 01:15:16,750
I won't tell anybody.

854
01:15:17,112 --> 01:15:18,887
You won't tell anyone what?

855
01:15:21,183 --> 01:15:23,754
Hello, Steiner. Hello, Fool

856
01:15:26,522 --> 01:15:28,195
What's that behind your back?

857
01:15:28,624 --> 01:15:29,864
Give it to me.

858
01:15:31,293 --> 01:15:32,431
LIESEL: Leave him alone!

859
01:15:32,594 --> 01:15:33,732
I said, give it to me!

860
01:15:36,198 --> 01:15:37,302
Give it to me!

861
01:15:40,536 --> 01:15:42,846
What was that? What was it?

862
01:15:43,038 --> 01:15:45,211
None of your business, German.

863
01:15:47,509 --> 01:15:48,579
(GROANS)

864
01:15:49,044 --> 01:15:50,079
LIESEL: Leave him!

865
01:15:55,717 --> 01:15:57,128
You're done for, Steiner.

866
01:15:58,887 --> 01:15:59,922
I'm reporting you.

867
01:16:00,088 --> 01:16:02,830
For what? Having a diary?

868
01:16:03,525 --> 01:16:05,766
I know you're up to something.

869
01:16:14,036 --> 01:16:15,174
Come on!

870
01:16:23,245 --> 01:16:24,417
Come on!

871
01:16:26,949 --> 01:16:28,223
What are you doing?

872
01:16:28,417 --> 01:16:31,227
I know where it is! I watched it!

873
01:16:32,788 --> 01:16:35,098
It's freezing, Rudy. You'll die in there.

874
01:16:38,360 --> 01:16:39,532
Rudy!

875
01:16:43,932 --> 01:16:45,036
Rudy?

876
01:16:47,703 --> 01:16:48,773
Rudy!

877
01:16:50,772 --> 01:16:51,944
Rudy?

878
01:16:53,709 --> 01:16:55,689
Rudy, I can't swim!

879
01:16:56,612 --> 01:16:57,852
Rudy!

880
01:16:58,780 --> 01:17:00,020
Please!

881
01:17:03,485 --> 01:17:04,828
Igor it!

882
01:17:06,054 --> 01:17:07,124
Rudy!

883
01:17:07,789 --> 01:17:09,268
I thought you were...

884
01:17:10,125 --> 01:17:11,103
Never mind.

885
01:17:11,827 --> 01:17:13,363
Trust me now?

886
01:17:14,596 --> 01:17:15,631
<i>Yes.</i>

887
01:17:15,831 --> 01:17:18,402
Then, how about that kiss?

888
01:17:18,600 --> 01:17:20,944
Come on. You're going to freeze.

889
01:17:37,819 --> 01:17:39,423
Good night...

890
01:17:39,621 --> 01:17:41,225
book thief.

891
01:17:45,961 --> 01:17:47,372
Good night, fish.

892
01:18:08,316 --> 01:18:10,091
I told Rudy.

893
01:18:14,620 --> 01:18:16,463
- Here, come on!
- I'm here!

894
01:18:16,789 --> 01:18:18,666
(CHILDREN CONTINUE CALLING)

895
01:18:30,837 --> 01:18:32,111
Look!

896
01:18:35,408 --> 01:18:36,648
LIESEL: What are they doing?

897
01:18:36,976 --> 01:18:39,855
Checking basements.
They checked my cousin's last night.

898
01:18:41,614 --> 01:18:42,592
For what?

899
01:18:44,183 --> 01:18:46,129
Can we get on with it now?

900
01:18:46,552 --> 01:18:47,792
BOY 1: Come on!

901
01:18:48,988 --> 01:18:50,661
BOY 2: Here! Pass it!

902
01:18:54,227 --> 01:18:55,205
RUDY: Are you nuts?

903
01:19:03,736 --> 01:19:04,714
I have to go inside.

904
01:19:05,071 --> 01:19:06,209
Oh, great.

905
01:19:06,406 --> 01:19:07,407
RUDY: She's hurt.

906
01:19:07,740 --> 01:19:08,844
Never stopped her before.

907
01:19:09,542 --> 01:19:10,646
I'm fine.

908
01:19:19,185 --> 01:19:21,062
- Mama!
- Why are you shouting?

909
01:19:21,254 --> 01:19:22,255
They're coming.

910
01:19:22,422 --> 01:19:23,423
Who?

911
01:19:23,623 --> 01:19:25,102
They're checking basements.

912
01:19:32,899 --> 01:19:34,276
Hans, come quickly!

913
01:19:35,234 --> 01:19:36,269
- What is it?
- Somebody is coming.

914
01:19:36,469 --> 01:19:38,176
They are checking basements.

915
01:19:39,739 --> 01:19:41,377
We have to hide him.

916
01:19:41,574 --> 01:19:43,611
Get him up here, under the bed.

917
01:19:44,777 --> 01:19:46,017
(CLATTERING)

918
01:19:46,946 --> 01:19:48,653
-Max!

919
01:19:48,748 --> 01:19:49,783
Max!

920
01:19:50,950 --> 01:19:52,224
Come on. Come on.

921
01:19:52,552 --> 01:19:55,556
So, do they give you a gun
when you join the army?

922
01:19:56,055 --> 01:19:57,033
Mama!

923
01:19:59,091 --> 01:20:00,263
Oh, my God.

924
01:20:01,060 --> 01:20:02,801
Hans, leave that!

925
01:20:03,596 --> 01:20:05,041
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

926
01:20:10,002 --> 01:20:13,108
Wolfy. What a surprise. How are you?

927
01:20:14,307 --> 01:20:15,809
You want Hans?

928
01:20:16,008 --> 01:20:17,078
Hans!

929
01:20:17,276 --> 01:20:19,779
No, <i>No, No.</i>
We're just checking people's basements.

930
01:20:19,979 --> 01:20:21,481
Oh, Liesel, will you get Herr Edel...

931
01:20:21,681 --> 01:20:23,490
-a glass of water?
- No need.

932
01:20:23,683 --> 01:20:24,889
This shouldn't take a second.

933
01:20:28,621 --> 01:20:29,759
You should bandage that.

934
01:20:29,956 --> 01:20:32,630
Oh, my God, Liesel! Yes!
Oh, would you do me a favor...

935
01:20:32,825 --> 01:20:35,396
and get me
the medicine chest? it's just on that...

936
01:20:35,595 --> 01:20:36,733
Where is the man trap?

937
01:20:37,864 --> 01:20:39,070
The what?

938
01:20:39,232 --> 01:20:40,404
The door to your basement.

939
01:20:40,800 --> 01:20:42,643
(BANGING)

940
01:20:43,169 --> 01:20:44,170
Ah!

941
01:20:44,270 --> 01:20:45,749
Wolfa.

942
01:20:45,938 --> 01:20:47,918
I heard you were coming.
I've been working, tidying up.

943
01:20:50,009 --> 01:20:51,283
Heard from who?

944
01:20:52,678 --> 01:20:54,453
Who was it collecting our washing?

945
01:20:54,881 --> 01:20:55,859
<i>Frau</i> Schneider.

946
01:20:56,048 --> 01:20:58,654
<i>Frau</i> Schneider, fa. She mentioned it.

947
01:20:58,851 --> 01:20:59,886
Come.

948
01:21:11,631 --> 01:21:12,974
WOLFGANG: ls there a light in here?

949
01:21:13,165 --> 01:21:14,701
HANS: Yes, of course.

950
01:21:15,234 --> 01:21:17,942
I should probably
throw most of this stuff out.

951
01:21:18,538 --> 01:21:21,542
You wouldn't believe what we
find in some people's basements.

952
01:21:21,741 --> 01:21:23,652
Oh, it wouldn't surprise me.

953
01:21:24,343 --> 01:21:26,414
Liesel, she is always playing down here.

954
01:21:26,512 --> 01:21:29,083
I keep telling her to get out in the fresh air.

955
01:21:35,488 --> 01:21:37,695
What is this about, anyway?

956
01:21:56,909 --> 01:21:57,910
WOLFGANG: What's this?

957
01:22:06,419 --> 01:22:07,489
My brushes.

958
01:22:11,691 --> 01:22:13,671
You should look after them better.

959
01:22:14,360 --> 01:22:16,840
Liesel, you know, she never listens to me.

960
01:22:16,929 --> 01:22:18,203
(CLATTERING)

961
01:22:23,069 --> 01:22:25,515
(SOFTLY) Still no work, eh, Hans?

962
01:22:26,038 --> 01:22:27,483
Not a lot.

963
01:22:29,041 --> 01:22:32,386
You should have
taken my advice and joined the party.

964
01:22:32,912 --> 01:22:34,619
Then your wife wouldn't
have to break her back...

965
01:22:34,814 --> 01:22:37,385
washing people's underwear to feed you.

966
01:22:39,652 --> 01:22:41,598
Isn't that right, Rosa?

967
01:22:42,622 --> 01:22:43,896
<i>Yes.</i>

968
01:22:45,558 --> 01:22:47,299
What's wrong with you?

969
01:22:49,261 --> 01:22:51,263
I've never heard you
turn down an opportunity...

970
01:22:51,464 --> 01:22:53,034
to give this one some lip.

971
01:22:53,332 --> 01:22:54,470
(swans)

972
01:22:54,767 --> 01:22:55,802
Well...

973
01:22:56,469 --> 01:23:01,111
if the Saukerl would
get off his lazy backside and help...

974
01:23:03,342 --> 01:23:05,754
to give him all the lip that he deserves.

975
01:23:08,080 --> 01:23:09,115
(CHUCKLING)

976
01:23:12,318 --> 01:23:14,298
I don't know how you live with her.

977
01:23:14,920 --> 01:23:16,160
Neither do I.

978
01:23:22,261 --> 01:23:24,400
Never too late to join, Hans.

979
01:23:30,703 --> 01:23:32,683
So, how's our basement?

980
01:23:32,872 --> 01:23:35,250
Perfectly useless. The ceiling is too low.

981
01:23:35,441 --> 01:23:36,613
What for?

982
01:23:36,809 --> 01:23:39,483
Air raid shelters.
Every street has to have one.

983
01:23:39,845 --> 01:23:41,119
You should be more careful.

984
01:23:41,280 --> 01:23:42,588
<i>Yes, Herr EdeL.</i>

985
01:23:53,459 --> 01:23:54,961
Hans...

986
01:23:57,830 --> 01:24:00,504
What if he does die?

987
01:24:03,002 --> 01:24:05,983
We can't just leave him there.

988
01:24:09,842 --> 01:24:12,618
The smell will give us away.

989
01:24:16,649 --> 01:24:19,027
Hans, I'm afraid.

990
01:24:21,387 --> 01:24:23,492
Look, if it happens...

991
01:24:24,223 --> 01:24:26,328
if he dies...

992
01:24:28,327 --> 01:24:30,739
we'll simply have to find a way.

993
01:24:32,898 --> 01:24:34,673
He's not dead yet.

994
01:24:39,805 --> 01:24:41,284
All right?

995
01:24:50,583 --> 01:24:52,062
(CHILDREN MURMURING)

996
01:24:59,558 --> 01:25:00,901
Frau Hubermann?

997
01:25:01,093 --> 01:25:02,970
I need to speak to Liesel.

998
01:25:03,996 --> 01:25:06,135
Of course. Liesel?

999
01:25:11,704 --> 01:25:12,739
- Ow!
-(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

1000
01:25:12,838 --> 01:25:14,545
What did you do with it, you little thief?

1001
01:25:14,740 --> 01:25:15,718
What, Mama?

1002
01:25:15,808 --> 01:25:16,912
Don't "what" me.

1003
01:25:17,176 --> 01:25:18,678
I have told you a hundred times

1004
01:25:18,778 --> 01:25:20,815
to leave that thing alone, but do you listen?

1005
01:25:26,719 --> 01:25:27,720
TEACHER: Back to work.

1006
01:25:32,958 --> 01:25:34,266
I'm sorry.

1007
01:25:35,060 --> 01:25:36,971
Mama, what is it?

1008
01:25:39,732 --> 01:25:41,143
It's Max, isn't it?

1009
01:25:41,867 --> 01:25:43,073
(SNIFFLES)

1010
01:25:48,974 --> 01:25:51,352
He said that this belongs to you.

1011
01:25:54,914 --> 01:25:56,120
Who said?

1012
01:25:58,317 --> 01:26:00,126
He woke up.

1013
01:26:00,319 --> 01:26:01,320
He's going to live!

1014
01:26:01,487 --> 01:26:02,522
Mama!

1015
01:26:08,360 --> 01:26:09,338
Careful.

1016
01:26:12,464 --> 01:26:14,501
I'm sorry if I hurt you.

1017
01:26:15,067 --> 01:26:17,638
I couldn't think of any other way to tell you.

1018
01:26:17,837 --> 01:26:19,817
I know it's silly of me. I know.

1019
01:26:20,005 --> 01:26:21,916
No, Mama, it's not.

1020
01:26:22,107 --> 01:26:23,108
Thank you.

1021
01:26:23,943 --> 01:26:26,787
Well, you'd better
wipe that smile off your face.

1022
01:26:28,013 --> 01:26:30,289
Just go back in there...

1023
01:26:30,482 --> 01:26:34,123
and act like I'm the witch, you know? Yes?

1024
01:26:34,653 --> 01:26:36,064
<i>Yes.</i>

1025
01:26:36,789 --> 01:26:39,497
Just know that...

1026
01:26:41,961 --> 01:26:43,531
that l ...

1027
01:26:46,498 --> 01:26:47,602
Go on.

1028
01:26:51,704 --> 01:26:53,911
Do you need a bit of help with that smile?

1029
01:27:01,981 --> 01:27:03,426
If I ever catch you...

1030
01:27:03,616 --> 01:27:05,095
doing that sort of thing again, so help me...

1031
01:27:05,284 --> 01:27:06,627
I will string you up by your toes.

1032
01:27:06,819 --> 01:27:08,924
<i>Do you hear me, Saumensch?</i>

1033
01:27:09,121 --> 01:27:10,361
Understood?

1034
01:27:36,515 --> 01:27:37,721
Max!

1035
01:27:37,917 --> 01:27:38,987
Max!

1036
01:27:46,258 --> 01:27:47,293
I knew you'd live.

1037
01:27:47,693 --> 01:27:50,139
With all that reading,
you wouldn't leave me in peace.

1038
01:27:51,196 --> 01:27:52,300
You heard me?

1039
01:27:52,498 --> 01:27:53,636
Of course.

1040
01:27:54,867 --> 01:27:55,845
Thank you.

1041
01:28:06,545 --> 01:28:07,751
So...

1042
01:28:10,749 --> 01:28:12,353
How's Rudy?

1043
01:28:17,523 --> 01:28:18,900
I don't know.

1044
01:28:19,091 --> 01:28:21,264
Rudy's a pain in the neck.

1045
01:28:25,030 --> 01:28:29,069
The only thing worse
than a boy you hate is a boy you like, right?

1046
01:28:31,070 --> 01:28:32,947
(SIRENS WAILING)

1047
01:28:33,038 --> 01:28:34,847
ROSA: Liesel, it's an air raid!

1048
01:28:38,310 --> 01:28:39,288
Go on, then.

1049
01:28:39,745 --> 01:28:41,247
What about you?

1050
01:28:41,447 --> 01:28:43,757
I'm here. I'll be fine.

1051
01:28:43,949 --> 01:28:45,587
It's a basement, isn't it?

1052
01:28:45,784 --> 01:28:47,058
<i>ROSA". Did you hear me, Saumensch?</i>

1053
01:28:47,252 --> 01:28:48,287
Yes, Mama.

1054
01:28:54,560 --> 01:28:56,369
(SIRENS CONTINUE WAILING)

1055
01:29:15,681 --> 01:29:17,092
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

1056
01:29:38,003 --> 01:29:39,812
(ACCORDION PLAYING WALTZ)

1057
01:30:06,532 --> 01:30:08,205
(EXPLOSIONS CONTINUE)

1058
01:30:16,208 --> 01:30:21,851
<i>NARRATOR: While 10,000 souls
hid their heads in fear and trembled...</i>

1059
01:30:22,081 --> 01:30:26,427
<i>one Jew thanked God
for the stars that blessed his eyes.</i>

1060
01:30:32,825 --> 01:30:34,600
(VEHICLE APPROACHING)

1061
01:30:54,379 --> 01:30:55,380
it's all I have.

1062
01:30:55,581 --> 01:30:56,685
I'm sorry.

1063
01:30:57,249 --> 01:30:59,889
I was saving it for
my husband's return, but...

1064
01:31:00,252 --> 01:31:02,198
Thank you. Very much.

1065
01:31:02,454 --> 01:31:04,331
(TIRES SCREECHING)

1066
01:31:11,663 --> 01:31:13,540
(BARKING)

1067
01:31:17,402 --> 01:31:18,506
He's a Jew.

1068
01:31:18,704 --> 01:31:19,842
They found his birth certificate.

1069
01:31:20,072 --> 01:31:22,211
He's a "Lehman" with one not two.

1070
01:31:23,108 --> 01:31:24,246
LEHMAN: Please!

1071
01:31:26,278 --> 01:31:28,019
My son is in the army!

1072
01:31:29,648 --> 01:31:30,786
He's fighting on the front!

1073
01:31:32,584 --> 01:31:33,892
- Please.
- In the car!

1074
01:31:33,986 --> 01:31:35,192
(GROANS)

1075
01:31:35,888 --> 01:31:37,128
Please!

1076
01:31:41,760 --> 01:31:42,738
You know me.

1077
01:31:43,228 --> 01:31:44,366
Please!

1078
01:31:45,497 --> 01:31:47,374
You know me! Please!

1079
01:31:47,599 --> 01:31:48,942
I'm German!

1080
01:31:50,335 --> 01:31:51,313
Please...

1081
01:31:51,603 --> 01:31:54,174
I've known this man
my whole life. We all have.

1082
01:31:54,573 --> 01:31:55,916
He's a good person.

1083
01:31:56,308 --> 01:31:57,343
What's your name?

1084
01:32:01,013 --> 01:32:02,822
Hans Hubermann.

1085
01:32:06,451 --> 01:32:08,522
- Please! He's a good man.
- Get back!

1086
01:32:09,021 --> 01:32:09,999
LIESEL: Papa!

1087
01:32:11,190 --> 01:32:12,168
Papa!

1088
01:32:13,492 --> 01:32:14,562
Liesel!

1089
01:32:34,313 --> 01:32:35,485
Rudy!

1090
01:32:38,383 --> 01:32:39,521
Rudy.

1091
01:32:49,061 --> 01:32:50,506
Keep still.

1092
01:32:50,696 --> 01:32:52,676
What was I thinking?

1093
01:32:53,832 --> 01:32:55,834
He took my name.

1094
01:32:57,903 --> 01:33:00,611
Christ on the cross, what have I done?

1095
01:33:00,706 --> 01:33:02,208
(SHUSHING)

1096
01:33:02,874 --> 01:33:06,014
I've ruined us! I've ruined us!

1097
01:33:07,012 --> 01:33:08,992
I'm sorry, Rosa.

1098
01:33:09,181 --> 01:33:11,024
I'm sorry.

1099
01:33:17,189 --> 01:33:18,930
I don't understand.

1100
01:33:22,060 --> 01:33:24,301
What did he do so wrong?

1101
01:33:26,398 --> 01:33:29,208
He reminded people of their humanity.

1102
01:33:31,536 --> 01:33:33,311
Can't he apologize?

1103
01:33:34,573 --> 01:33:36,018
To who?

1104
01:33:37,042 --> 01:33:38,020
Hitler?

1105
01:33:41,413 --> 01:33:43,393
Will they take him away?

1106
01:33:43,582 --> 01:33:44,617
I don't know.

1107
01:33:45,584 --> 01:33:46,858
But...

1108
01:33:48,120 --> 01:33:50,532
if they come and find me here...

1109
01:33:51,757 --> 01:33:53,395
they'll take all of you away.

1110
01:33:58,230 --> 01:33:59,937
No, Max.

1111
01:34:01,800 --> 01:34:03,404
I have to, Liesel.

1112
01:34:05,704 --> 01:34:06,842
I'm sorry.

1113
01:34:07,973 --> 01:34:09,452
But you promised.

1114
01:34:10,876 --> 01:34:12,583
It's for your own good.

1115
01:34:14,646 --> 01:34:15,989
For your family.

1116
01:34:17,282 --> 01:34:19,284
But you're my family.

1117
01:34:34,132 --> 01:34:36,339
You've kept me alive, Liesel.

1118
01:34:37,803 --> 01:34:39,111
Don't ever forget that.

1119
01:34:39,304 --> 01:34:40,612
I can't lose someone else.

1120
01:34:40,706 --> 01:34:42,811
I'm not lost to you, Liesel.

1121
01:34:43,141 --> 01:34:46,281
You'll always be able
to find me in your words.

1122
01:34:46,978 --> 01:34:48,980
That's where I'll live on.

1123
01:34:54,953 --> 01:34:56,057
Max...

1124
01:34:57,422 --> 01:34:58,833
please.

1125
01:35:00,926 --> 01:35:02,337
Thank you.

1126
01:35:09,968 --> 01:35:11,140
Here.

1127
01:35:11,870 --> 01:35:15,044
It's two blankets and a pair of socks.

1128
01:35:15,374 --> 01:35:17,411
And a nice piece of cheese
that I've been saving.

1129
01:35:17,609 --> 01:35:18,849
Rosa...

1130
01:35:19,211 --> 01:35:20,281
it's yours.

1131
01:36:17,369 --> 01:36:19,007
Come. Liesel.

1132
01:36:19,204 --> 01:36:20,706
Leave her.

1133
01:36:25,177 --> 01:36:26,554
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

1134
01:36:42,294 --> 01:36:43,295
Hans?

1135
01:36:45,564 --> 01:36:47,202
I'll get my coat.

1136
01:36:55,907 --> 01:36:57,818
You a re Herr Steiner?

1137
01:37:02,080 --> 01:37:03,252
What?

1138
01:37:04,449 --> 01:37:06,793
I'm here to talk about your son, Rudy.

1139
01:37:07,486 --> 01:37:08,726
Rudy Steiner.

1140
01:37:09,988 --> 01:37:12,093
He lives next door.

1141
01:37:12,891 --> 01:37:14,564
What do you want with him?

1142
01:37:31,910 --> 01:37:34,288
He's been selected for elite training.

1143
01:37:35,180 --> 01:37:36,818
He starts in the summer.

1144
01:37:39,251 --> 01:37:41,754
I'm sorry, Barbra.

1145
01:37:52,964 --> 01:37:54,568
Hans Hubermann?

1146
01:38:13,985 --> 01:38:15,862
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

1147
01:38:29,801 --> 01:38:32,407
What's "conscripted"?

1148
01:39:03,168 --> 01:39:05,011
(MAN SPEAKING GERMAN ON PA)

1149
01:39:13,378 --> 01:39:15,756
Look how you've grown.

1150
01:39:15,947 --> 01:39:17,790
I had not noticed.

1151
01:39:19,284 --> 01:39:20,627
I will miss you.

1152
01:39:20,819 --> 01:39:22,799
Everyone's leaving.

1153
01:39:22,988 --> 01:39:24,058
Even Rudy.

1154
01:39:24,255 --> 01:39:26,599
Rudy is going to be fine.

1155
01:39:26,791 --> 01:39:30,238
Look after your Mama, fa?
She's not as strong as she makes out.

1156
01:39:30,428 --> 01:39:31,668
I know.

1157
01:39:31,830 --> 01:39:33,070
Good girl.

1158
01:39:44,009 --> 01:39:45,488
Papa?

1159
01:39:48,313 --> 01:39:49,724
Come home.

1160
01:40:38,263 --> 01:40:39,537
(SOBBING)

1161
01:40:55,447 --> 01:40:56,482
What do you think?

1162
01:40:59,851 --> 01:41:01,455
LIESEL: The shoes let you down.

1163
01:41:03,588 --> 01:41:04,896
And the face.

1164
01:41:05,657 --> 01:41:06,727
Coming?

1165
01:41:07,392 --> 01:41:08,894
Where are you going?

1166
01:41:09,861 --> 01:41:12,364
Isn't it obvious? I'm running away.

1167
01:41:18,036 --> 01:41:19,982
LIESEL: Have you thought this through?

1168
01:41:20,171 --> 01:41:21,479
RUDY: Yes.

1169
01:41:22,040 --> 01:41:23,951
I don't want to die.

1170
01:41:24,142 --> 01:41:26,986
There. All thought through.

1171
01:41:28,713 --> 01:41:31,353
Rudy, where are you going to stay?

1172
01:41:31,549 --> 01:41:34,291
<i>"You"?</i> What <i>about "we"?</i>

1173
01:41:35,053 --> 01:41:37,294
I didn't think you were this serious.

1174
01:41:37,489 --> 01:41:38,559
What do you call this?

1175
01:41:40,391 --> 01:41:41,836
Packed lunch?

1176
01:41:42,660 --> 01:41:45,800
Is there anything in there
besides your soccer ball?

1177
01:41:53,037 --> 01:41:55,017
I miss my dad.

1178
01:42:00,011 --> 01:42:02,514
I don't even know if he's alive.

1179
01:42:08,019 --> 01:42:09,896
I'm not ready.

1180
01:42:11,055 --> 01:42:14,002
I want to grow up before I die.

1181
01:42:16,361 --> 01:42:17,601
So did my brother.

1182
01:42:21,099 --> 01:42:22,271
I'm sorry.

1183
01:42:25,537 --> 01:42:27,244
I didn't ask for this.

1184
01:42:27,438 --> 01:42:28,974
Who would?

1185
01:42:31,643 --> 01:42:33,782
I hate Hitler.

1186
01:42:34,212 --> 01:42:35,384
Me, too.

1187
01:42:38,750 --> 01:42:40,730
I hate Hitler!

1188
01:42:42,587 --> 01:42:43,998
I hate Hitler!

1189
01:42:44,189 --> 01:42:45,862
I hate Hitler!

1190
01:42:46,124 --> 01:42:48,661
- I hate Hitler!
- Hitler is a monkey's ass!

1191
01:42:48,893 --> 01:42:50,304
Stick you, Hitler!

1192
01:43:02,207 --> 01:43:04,016
You're all I've got, Rudy.

1193
01:43:08,947 --> 01:43:10,119
Let's go home.

1194
01:43:53,057 --> 01:43:54,229
(AIRPLANES DRONING)

1195
01:43:55,827 --> 01:43:57,829
<i>NARRATOR: The bombs were
coming thicker now.</i>

1196
01:43:58,029 --> 01:43:59,372
(EXPLOSIONS)

1197
01:43:59,464 --> 01:44:00,738
<i>It's probably fair to say...</i>

1198
01:44:00,932 --> 01:44:05,278
<i>that no one was able
to serve the Fuhrer as loyally as me.</i>

1199
01:44:07,538 --> 01:44:09,540
(EXPLOSIONS CONTINUE)

1200
01:44:31,029 --> 01:44:32,133
(LOUD EXPLOSION)

1201
01:44:32,230 --> 01:44:33,573
(BABIES CRYING)

1202
01:44:33,798 --> 01:44:36,142
(ACCORDION PLAYING WALTZ FAINTLY)

1203
01:44:46,811 --> 01:44:50,224
There once was a ghost of a boy...

1204
01:44:51,316 --> 01:44:53,990
who liked to live in the shadows of things...

1205
01:44:55,086 --> 01:44:56,997
so he wouldn't frighten people.

1206
01:44:57,188 --> 01:44:59,065
- What was that?
- Who's speaking?

1207
01:45:00,858 --> 01:45:02,565
What are you doing?

1208
01:45:02,760 --> 01:45:04,501
Telling a story.

1209
01:45:04,696 --> 01:45:05,731
Why?

1210
01:45:05,930 --> 01:45:06,965
Whose boy?

1211
01:45:08,099 --> 01:45:09,134
She's telling a story.

1212
01:45:09,300 --> 01:45:10,301
Speak up.

1213
01:45:10,735 --> 01:45:11,839
(SHUSHES)

1214
01:45:12,003 --> 01:45:13,004
Start again.

1215
01:45:15,940 --> 01:45:18,580
There once was a ghost of a boy...

1216
01:45:18,776 --> 01:45:20,983
who liked to live in the shadows,

1217
01:45:21,145 --> 01:45:23,352
so he wouldn't frighten people.

1218
01:45:25,083 --> 01:45:29,759
His job was to
wait for his sister, who was still alive.

1219
01:45:31,689 --> 01:45:33,930
She wasn't afraid of the dark...

1220
01:45:34,125 --> 01:45:37,800
because she knew
that's where her brother was.

1221
01:45:38,629 --> 01:45:39,801
(EXPLOSION)

1222
01:45:39,964 --> 01:45:41,375
Go on.

1223
01:45:42,367 --> 01:45:46,440
At night, when darkness came to her room...

1224
01:45:47,572 --> 01:45:49,950
she would tell her brother about the day.

1225
01:45:50,141 --> 01:45:54,612
She would remind him
how the sun felt on his skin...

1226
01:45:54,812 --> 01:45:57,224
and what the air felt like to breathe...

1227
01:45:57,382 --> 01:45:58,861
(LOUD EXPLOSION)

1228
01:46:00,918 --> 01:46:05,128
Or how snow felt
on his tongue. And that reminded her...

1229
01:46:05,556 --> 01:46:07,832
that she was still alive.

1230
01:46:10,395 --> 01:46:11,738
(EXPLOSION)

1231
01:46:14,232 --> 01:46:15,575
(ALL CLAMORING)

1232
01:46:16,167 --> 01:46:17,544
(SIREN WAILING)

1233
01:46:23,007 --> 01:46:24,213
Gentlemen...

1234
01:46:25,109 --> 01:46:26,554
how is everybody?

1235
01:46:26,978 --> 01:46:30,050
Look at this one.
They are starting to conscript grandfathers.

1236
01:46:30,148 --> 01:46:31,218
(ALL LAUGHING)

1237
01:46:31,315 --> 01:46:35,627
Hey, old man. Old man,
are they your own teeth?

1238
01:46:38,890 --> 01:46:40,563
(EXPLOSIONS CONTINUE)

1239
01:46:55,473 --> 01:46:57,009
(SIREN WAILING)

1240
01:47:02,180 --> 01:47:05,593
Together, they sat in the forest...

1241
01:47:05,783 --> 01:47:08,855
and watched the sun rise.

1242
01:47:09,053 --> 01:47:12,296
And as he disappeared
back into the shadows...

1243
01:47:12,490 --> 01:47:15,903
she waved goodbye for the last time.

1244
01:47:18,463 --> 01:47:20,101
Oh, Liesel.

1245
01:47:37,315 --> 01:47:39,420
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

1246
01:48:04,208 --> 01:48:05,346
LIESEL: Max?

1247
01:48:06,611 --> 01:48:07,589
Max?

1248
01:48:08,346 --> 01:48:09,552
Max!

1249
01:48:14,852 --> 01:48:15,853
Max!

1250
01:48:16,921 --> 01:48:18,264
<i>Saumensch!</i>

1251
01:48:18,523 --> 01:48:20,230
What are you up to?

1252
01:48:20,424 --> 01:48:21,425
Max?

1253
01:48:22,627 --> 01:48:24,334
- Liesel!
- Max?

1254
01:48:25,429 --> 01:48:27,033
- Do you know Max?
- Liesel!

1255
01:48:27,632 --> 01:48:28,702
Do you know Max?

1256
01:48:31,402 --> 01:48:32,779
Max?

1257
01:48:35,973 --> 01:48:37,452
Do you know Max?

1258
01:48:44,949 --> 01:48:46,860
Get out of here, you stupid girl!

1259
01:48:49,220 --> 01:48:50,221
Liesel!

1260
01:48:50,955 --> 01:48:53,162
I won't forget you. I won't forget you.

1261
01:48:53,457 --> 01:48:54,959
I won't forget you.

1262
01:48:55,159 --> 01:48:57,036
I won't forget you, Max.

1263
01:48:57,929 --> 01:48:58,930
Liesel!

1264
01:49:05,169 --> 01:49:06,204
Go out!

1265
01:49:07,038 --> 01:49:08,016
Liesel!

1266
01:49:20,585 --> 01:49:23,088
You're too much
like your father, you know that?

1267
01:49:25,189 --> 01:49:27,430
What's wrong with that?

1268
01:49:30,828 --> 01:49:32,330
Nothing.

1269
01:49:39,637 --> 01:49:41,844
Hey, Saumensch, want to play?

1270
01:49:42,039 --> 01:49:44,144
No, not today.

1271
01:49:44,642 --> 01:49:47,020
Then let's steal something.

1272
01:49:47,211 --> 01:49:49,623
I don't steal. I borrow.

1273
01:49:50,281 --> 01:49:55,060
Then let's go borrow
Franz Deutscher's bike and get out of here.

1274
01:49:56,287 --> 01:49:57,322
Can't you see I'm reading?

1275
01:49:58,789 --> 01:50:00,029
Are you still angry with me?

1276
01:50:01,892 --> 01:50:03,132
For what?

1277
01:50:05,196 --> 01:50:06,766
Saving you.

1278
01:50:07,465 --> 01:50:08,876
No, Rudy.

1279
01:50:09,166 --> 01:50:10,372
You're very brave.

1280
01:50:10,601 --> 01:50:12,342
(TRUCK APPROACHING)

1281
01:50:26,517 --> 01:50:27,894
Papa!

1282
01:50:30,154 --> 01:50:31,462
You're home!

1283
01:50:38,996 --> 01:50:40,737
What is it, my girl?

1284
01:50:43,200 --> 01:50:44,304
(swans)

1285
01:50:46,570 --> 01:50:47,981
MY girl.

1286
01:50:48,873 --> 01:50:50,216
MY girl.

1287
01:50:57,748 --> 01:50:59,523
(PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)

1288
01:51:14,598 --> 01:51:16,942
it's nice to hear you play.

1289
01:51:17,234 --> 01:51:19,009
I can't hear properly.

1290
01:51:21,105 --> 01:51:22,709
I'm going to bed.

1291
01:51:23,774 --> 01:51:26,015
Don't stay up too late, you two.

1292
01:51:38,756 --> 01:51:41,134
Your mama told me what you did.

1293
01:51:44,762 --> 01:51:46,366
I shouldn't have.

1294
01:51:46,764 --> 01:51:48,573
Maybe you had to.

1295
01:51:52,069 --> 01:51:54,413
I keep thinking about Max.

1296
01:51:55,339 --> 01:51:56,579
Wondering where he is.

1297
01:51:58,008 --> 01:51:59,578
Me, too.

1298
01:52:01,479 --> 01:52:03,584
I'm not sure what it all meant.

1299
01:52:05,015 --> 01:52:07,154
Everything he went through.

1300
01:52:07,918 --> 01:52:09,829
Everything we did.

1301
01:52:12,923 --> 01:52:15,335
We were just being people.

1302
01:52:16,594 --> 01:52:17,868
That's what people do.

1303
01:52:20,865 --> 01:52:22,139
Liesel...

1304
01:52:23,300 --> 01:52:25,246
you are all grown up.

1305
01:52:30,674 --> 01:52:35,248
<i>LIESEL: AH I have
learned is that life makes no promises.</i>

1306
01:52:35,446 --> 01:52:37,357
<i>So I had better get started.</i>

1307
01:52:38,015 --> 01:52:40,552
<i>I have always tried to ignore it...</i>

1308
01:52:40,951 --> 01:52:44,057
<i>but I know this all started with a train...</i>

1309
01:52:45,890 --> 01:52:47,631
<i>and some snow...</i>

1310
01:52:48,793 --> 01:52:50,238
<i>and my brother.</i>

1311
01:52:53,497 --> 01:52:57,172
<i>Outside the car,
the world was thrown inside a snow-shaker.</i>

1312
01:52:57,501 --> 01:52:59,503
<i>And on a place called Heaven Street...</i>

1313
01:52:59,703 --> 01:53:03,446
<i>a man with an accordion
heart and a woman cloaked in thunder...</i>

1314
01:53:03,641 --> 01:53:05,211
<i>waited for their new daughter.</i>

1315
01:53:06,410 --> 01:53:08,083
(PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)

1316
01:53:12,850 --> 01:53:16,821
<i>He lived under our stairs
like a quiet owl with no wings...</i>

1317
01:53:17,021 --> 01:53:20,002
<i>until the sun forgot what his face was.</i>

1318
01:53:26,664 --> 01:53:28,666
<i>The book floated down the river...</i>

1319
01:53:28,866 --> 01:53:32,643
<i>like a red fish being chased
by a yellow-haired bay.</i>

1320
01:53:42,913 --> 01:53:45,587
<i>For Max, who gave me eyes.</i>

1321
01:54:12,276 --> 01:54:14,449
Good night, Your Majesty.

1322
01:54:25,756 --> 01:54:29,898
NARRATOR: <i>I've always quite liked
the image of me with a sickle and cape.</i>

1323
01:54:30,094 --> 01:54:32,597
<i>Dark and formidable.</i>

1324
01:54:32,796 --> 01:54:37,006
<i>Unfortunately, I'm far more
ordinary and commonplace.</i>

1325
01:54:39,003 --> 01:54:42,917
<i>No one intended to destroy
a street named after Heaven.</i>

1326
01:54:43,674 --> 01:54:46,154
<i>It was a misread on a map.</i>

1327
01:54:46,343 --> 01:54:48,653
<i>No sirens that evening.</i>

1328
01:54:50,014 --> 01:54:52,392
<i>First were Rudy's brothers.</i>

1329
01:54:56,186 --> 01:54:58,723
<i>I read their simple dreams.</i>

1330
01:55:02,960 --> 01:55:05,463
<i>Then, I kissed his mother.</i>

1331
01:55:08,098 --> 01:55:11,978
<i>And stole the meanness
from Franz German's heart.</i>

1332
01:55:17,141 --> 01:55:19,849
<i>Rosa, I caught mid-snore.</i>

1333
01:55:20,678 --> 01:55:24,125
<i>I could swear I heard her call me a bastard.</i>

1334
01:55:24,315 --> 01:55:29,958
<i>Then I felt her regrets
for not sharing more of her very big heart.</i>

1335
01:55:30,854 --> 01:55:35,803
<i>As for Hans, his soul was
lighter than a child 's.</i>

1336
01:55:36,160 --> 01:55:40,040
<i>I felt his itch
for one last tune on his accordion...</i>

1337
01:55:40,664 --> 01:55:43,110
<i>and heard his final thought...</i>

1338
01:55:45,035 --> 01:55:46,673
<i>"Lies e]. "</i>

1339
01:56:33,717 --> 01:56:35,128
(CHORD PLAYING)

1340
01:56:39,857 --> 01:56:41,097
Over here!

1341
01:56:47,097 --> 01:56:48,599
Just over.

1342
01:56:56,740 --> 01:56:57,741
Your hand.

1343
01:57:10,654 --> 01:57:12,895
Mama? Papa?

